      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation outputs must be compared against experimental data using an appropriate validation metric.",
      "rationale": "Velocity profiles compared at six measurement planes using the E-metric (normalized RMS error). E-metric values range from 0.04 to 0.11 across planes, all below the 0.15 acceptance threshold. Hemolysis index predictions compared using relative error; all within ±12% of experimental mean."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The quantities of interest used in validation must be directly relevant to the clinical decision.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the relative hemolysis index (RH), which is the same metric used in the regulatory submission acceptance criterion (RH < 1 relative to predicate). Secondary QoI (peak shear stress, exposure time distribution) are mechanistically linked to hemolysis prediction. Relevance is direct."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments must be sufficiently similar to the COU in geometry, flow regime, and fluid properties.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump, which is geometrically representative of the device class. Flow regimes (Re 2,000–18,000) span the COU operating range. Blood analog fluid (glycerin-water) properties match within 5% of whole blood at 37 °C. Validation-to-COU similarity is high."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated; residuals must reach specified tolerances.",
      "rationale": "All simulations converged to residual levels below 1×10⁻⁵ for continuity and momentum equations. Mass imbalance across inlet/outlet planes is less than 0.01%. Steady-state solutions confirmed by monitoring hemolysis index over 500 additional iterations after nominal convergence."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup must be reviewed by an independent analyst to detect user errors.",
      "rationale": "An independent CFD analyst reviewed all simulation setup files, boundary condition specifications, and post-processing scripts prior to production runs. Two minor errors (incorrect turbulence intensity specification at one operating point) were identified and corrected. Final setup approved by reviewer."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The mathematical model form must be justified for the physics of the COU.",
      "rationale": "Reynolds-Averaged Navier-Stokes (RANS) with SST k-ω turbulence closure selected based on published benchmark comparisons for rotary blood pump flows. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power-law model is the regulatory standard for this device class. Model form uncertainty estimated at ±15% on RH, within acceptable bounds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Sensitivity of model outputs to uncertain inputs must be quantified.",
      "rationale": "One-at-a-time sensitivity analysis performed on six uncertain input parameters (fluid viscosity, pump speed tolerance, gap clearance, inlet velocity profile, blood damage model coefficients, wall roughness). Hemolysis index sensitivity to blood damage model coefficients is highest (±18%); all other parameters contribute less than ±8%. Results documented in the uncertainty register."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation test samples must be representative of the device population.",
      "rationale": "Three physical pump units drawn from the same manufacturing lot were used in bench testing. Unit-to-unit variability in hemolysis index was 4.2% (CV), confirming that a single representative unit is sufficient at MRL 3. Sample provenance and dimensional inspection records are archived."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Boundary conditions and material parameters used in simulation must be demonstrably equivalent to those present in the clinical COU.",
      "rationale": "This factor was judged by the assessment team to be inapplicable to the present COU because the validation experiments were conducted using the same nominal boundary conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature) as specified for the clinical operating envelope. Since no extrapolation of boundary conditions was performed, formal equivalency assessment was considered unnecessary. The factor has therefore not been formally evaluated against the MRL 3 required level. Note: the appropriate encoding for a factor that genuinely does not apply would be factorStatus 'not-applicable'; the use of 'not-assessed' here reflects the team's informal disposition rather than a documented scoping decision, leaving this factor unresolved at an elevated model risk level."
    }
  ],
